<div id="review_1358814253" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1358814253" />
    <a title="Love of Hopeless Causes" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45710184-love-of-hopeless-causes"><img alt="Love of Hopeless Causes" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582120509p2/45710184.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1358814253?book_show_action=true">Aug 08, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Love of Hopeless Causes" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Love of Hopeless Causes" href="/user/show/45710184-love-of-hopeless-causes">Love of Hopeless Causes</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780515035216" href="/book/show/2295172.I_Have_No_Mouth_I_Must_Scream">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1358814253" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8289105821620827005">Transhumanists supposedly believe they will download their consciousness onto computers, so they are free to explore the galaxy unburdened by meatspace. Having read many stories where the computer goes to Nutsville, the last thing I want is to be eternally damned to live grafted on some loopy addled microchip. If you want to know what that hell might be like, read this, otherwise don&apos;t bother. The comic book is easier to follow than the audiobook. <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1453112204i/17781517.jpg' width='400' height='200' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>I just read the title story, though I read the o</span>
  <span id="freeText8289105821620827005" style="display:none">Transhumanists supposedly believe they will download their consciousness onto computers, so they are free to explore the galaxy unburdened by meatspace. Having read many stories where the computer goes to Nutsville, the last thing I want is to be eternally damned to live grafted on some loopy addled microchip. If you want to know what that hell might be like, read this, otherwise don't bother. The comic book is easier to follow than the audiobook. <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1453112204i/17781517.jpg" width="400" height="200" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>I just read the title story, though I read the others years ago. I've read three formats: print, comic, and audio. It's just an opinion, not an argument, but here goes. Opinions change over time.<br><br>It's just one giant atmospheric hell piece. What is the story goal? *spoilers* Survive. Are we shown how they survived? No, we are shown how they hopelessly died. A failure ending, which means the story is sad. That's not necessarily a "story" failure, but it isn't very satisfying. <br><br>What the characters are has little impact on the story, except for the Benny the chimp-thing/former professor. Because AM can morph them, the characters feel shallow and interchangeable. In most stories the characters struggle towards a goal. Here they struggle very little, mostly just complaining. Very tell, little show, except the opening corpse. <br><br>The female screws involuntary, cries and is passive, except when getting the big D from Benny. Is that a walking stereotype?<br><br>AM is a voyeur sadist pervert, when, what good would revenge be to a computer? Most illogical. I don't understand it or sympathize with it. <br>The characters are eternally alive, but certain they can't escape. Humans usually despair and cease moving around. If the computer can make them immortal, did it develop this tech?<br><br> I'm certain this was remarkable when written, but every novel belongs to its age, and all fade in relevance, on a long enough timeline.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8289105821620827005" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


